post_text:
The NJ Primary Election is tomorrow, July 7. Make sure your voice is heard in one of the following ways:
.
.
.
.
1. Sign, seal, and mail your ballot in. Your ballot MUST be postmarked by July 7 and received on or before July 14. Copy and paste to track your ballot: https://bit.ly/2NSrBlW
2. Sign, seal, and return your ballot to a secure ballot drop box by 8pm on July 7. In Newark, the box is at City Hall on the Green St side!
3. Sign, seal, and return your ballot in-person to the Board of Elections by 8pm on Election Day, July 7!
4. Vote in-person at a polling location on July 7, using a provisional paper ballot. Copy and paste to find your nearest polling location: https://bit.ly/3eONU86

post_text:
Students - we'd love to see you at our virtual community meeting today! The link to join for your council is in your PPCS inbox.
.
.
.
.
Video Conference Call ‘Netiquette’ for Students
- Your video is on.
- With the exception of students in the ACT Prep class, you begin joining the video call between 2:50 and 3:00 p.m.
- You are dressed appropriately and are in a space with good lighting.
- You have muted yourself. Only unmute yourself if you are called on to answer a question.
- You use the chat feature to ask any questions you have about the discussion.
- Besides your means for your video conference, you are technology and distraction-free.

post_text:
#blackouttuesday
.
.
.
.
.
In protest of the ongoing and targeted harassment and violation of rights within communities of color and in solidarity with those actively working to dismantle the racist structures upon which our nation was built, business has stopped for many companies and organizations today. As an organization, we have decided to keep school open for the day. We’ve made this choice in order to provide continuity for our students. If they need help with school work, space to process with their Council, or mental health services, it’s important that we’re there to provide that.

post_text: We have just been informed that one of our staff members was in contact with someone who was in close proximity to another person that has a confirmed case of COVID-19 (Coronavirus). The staff member has no symptoms. Out of an abundance of caution, we will be dismissing all students and staff immediately and doing a deep cleaning of our facilities. All students will be emailed their learning packets by 5:00 PM today to continue instruction. To emphasize, there are no reported cases of COVID-19 on our campus. We will be in touch once we have more information regarding the reopening of our building. Please email info@peoplesprep.org if you have any questions or concerns.

post_text:
Over the holiday season, it was reported that Newark District Superintendent requested that the New Jersey Department of Education close People's Prep.

To be clear, this report was a complete shock to each of us at People's Prep. Unfortunately, there was no prior warning from Mr. Leon, and other than what has been reported in the press, we have no additional information from the school district.

This week, People's Prep will be issuing a formal response to Mr. Leon's letter, and we will be following up with a letter to our community very shortly. Additionally, we are hosting a meeting for People's Prep parents and guardians in the school's cafeteria this Thursday, January 9th at 6:00 pm to discuss the New Jersey charter school renewal process, the context of Mr. Leon's letter to the Commissioner, and ways that parents can support our school community at this time. We hope to see you there.
text:
Over the holiday season, it was reported that Newark District Superintendent requested that the New Jersey Department of Education close People's Prep.

To be clear, this report was a complete shock to each of us at People's Prep. Unfortunately, there was no prior warning from Mr. Leon, and other than what has been reported in the press, we have no additional information from the school district.

This week, People's Prep will be issuing a formal response to Mr. Leon's letter, and we will be following up with a letter to our community very shortly. Additionally, we are hosting a meeting for People's Prep parents and guardians in the school's cafeteria this Thursday, January 9th at 6:00 pm to discuss the New Jersey charter school renewal process, the context of Mr. Leon's letter to the Commissioner, and ways that parents can support our school community at this time. We hope to see you there.

The holiday season is upon us, and do you know what that means? It's almost #GivingTuesday! Mark your calendar for Tuesday, December 3 and consider making the Friends of People's Prep your charity of choice!

Your donation will support high school seniors like Amberlee (pictured) who, like many of her peers, has already been accepted to college.

Your donation will benefit our more than 400 alumni who are currently enrolled in undergraduate studies and trade schools.

And your donation will help People's Preparatory Charter School to provide the resources and services necessary to ensuring the EVERY student, regardless of circumstance, graduates from the college of their choice.

Can't wait until #GivingTuesday? Donate now here: http://friendsofpeoplesprep.org/#donate

post_text:
Dear Parents and Caregivers,

Earlier this morning, one of People’s Prep’s fire alarms was activated, causing a momentary break from our academics.

Students and staff evacuated the building in an orderly fashion, Newark’s fire department was on the scene, and we were given the all clear. Our community reentered the building and continued their day.

Upon review, the remnants of a small fire were found in the first floor boys' locker room. The activity did not spread beyond the discovered location, and other than the evacuation, no one was affected. We are currently investigating how that fire started and will update you when we have more information. Please feel free to contact the school if you have any concerns or questions.

Thank you.
text:
Dear Parents and Caregivers,

Earlier this morning, one of People’s Prep’s fire alarms was activated, causing a momentary break from our academics.

Students and staff evacuated the building in an orderly fashion, Newark’s fire department was on the scene, and we were given the all clear. Our community reentered the building and continued their day.

Upon review, the remnants of a small fire were found in the first floor boys' locker room. The activity did not spread beyond the discovered location, and other than the evacuation, no one was affected. We are currently investigating how that fire started and will update you when we have more information. Please feel free to contact the school if you have any concerns or questions.

Thank you.
